Yes , bariatric surgery can be covered by Medicare under some conditions . Some of the conditions are that the patient 's BMI -LRB- Body Mass Index -RRB- must over 35 , they have obtained a psychological evaluation and ascertained in several ways that weight loss surgery is the best option , and have a health condition connected to being overweight that will be helped by having bariatric surgery .
Medicare can cover gastric bypass surgery under certain conditions . Some of those are : 1 -RRB- BMI must be 35 or greater . 2 -RRB- There must be at least one health condition related to weight . 3 -RRB- There must be documentation of failure to lose weight by other methods . 4 -RRB- A psychological evaluation is required . 5 -RRB- Other medical treatments for weight loss have been ruled out . 6 -RRB- The provider and type of surgery must be approved by Medicare .
Medicare will pay for weight loss surgery if the BMI is over 35 , if there is a health condition related to obesity that will be cured or alleviated by losing weight through the weight loss surgery , if weight loss must occur before treatment can be effectively undertaken for another health problem , and if other treatments are not expected to work to produce sufficient weight loss . There is a psychological evaluation done prior to surgery to make sure it should be done .
Yes , Medicare will pay for a duodenal switch if there is evidence that the weight loss surgery is medically necessary . Among other things , the patient 's BMI must be 35 or more and there must be a health condition that will be alleviated or cured by losing a lot of weight .
Medicare will pay for laparoscopic adjustable gastric band if the following three conditions are met : 1 -RRB- You must have a BMI of 35 or over at the time of surgery ; 2 -RRB- You must have a qualifying health condition associated with your being overweight that losing weight through gastric banding would help ; and 3 -RRB- You must complete a 6 month Physician Supervised Weight Loss Program proximate to the time of the surgery .
